00:01:39.560 --> 00:01:40.460
and eating right.

00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:43.640
I mean, I was eating quinoa
before quinoa was cool,

00:01:43.640 --> 00:01:46.005
when it was like $15 a pound.

00:01:46.005 --> 00:01:46.880
You know what I mean?

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:50.150
You could only find it at
certain specialty stores.

00:01:50.150 --> 00:01:52.910
And with this, I decided
that I felt the need

00:01:52.910 --> 00:01:56.035
to educate friends and family.

00:01:56.035 --> 00:01:56.910
You know what I mean?

00:01:56.910 --> 00:02:01.150
And by educating, being like,
oh, what's on your plate there?

00:02:01.150 --> 00:02:02.930
Ooh, pizza, again?

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:04.610
What are you eating?

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:07.400
I cared so much about
health that I wanted people

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:08.720
to have this knowledge.

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:11.570
I wanted people to get
excited about eating

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:14.690
fruits and vegetables,
and eating quinoa,

00:02:14.690 --> 00:02:16.790
and all of these things.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:19.430
And I had this judgmental
approach, though.

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:23.540
And all of this came to a head
in the Pittsburgh airport.

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:25.250
So let me tell you this story.

00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:27.920
It was right after I graduated.

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:30.800
I was on my way to a
nutrition conference.

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:34.130
So I had just got out
of Western Pennsylvania,

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:36.394
the mecca of meat and potatoes.

00:02:36.394 --> 00:02:38.810
I don't know if anyone has
ever been to Pittsburgh before,

00:02:38.810 --> 00:02:41.360
but we put fries on salad.

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:45.410
So I was like, oh, I'm going
to be with all of my nutrition

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:46.790
people, all of my health peeps.

00:02:46.790 --> 00:02:49.520
There's going to be 5,000
of us at this conference.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.830
We're going to be doing
kale shots off yoga mats.

00:02:51.830 --> 00:02:54.150
It's going to get
real crazy up in here.

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.540
So I'm a recovering
Type A perfectionist.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:59.240
So I go to the airport like 10
hours early, because I'm like,

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.400
am I going to-- you know,
I don't want to be late.

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:03.590
So I get to the airport early.

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:05.750
And I was like, you know what?

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:09.170
This would be a great time
to write a blog about the six

00:03:09.170 --> 00:03:13.410
benefits of juicing kale and why
you need to do it in your life.

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:16.940
So I get to the airport
early, and I decided to write.

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:20.720
So I look over at this
little section in there.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:23.662
And there was
probably 10 tables,

00:03:23.662 --> 00:03:24.870
and no one was sitting there.

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:25.870
And I was like,
oh, this is great.

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:26.620
I'll go sit there.

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:27.810
This is perfect.

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:29.290
So I go.

00:03:29.290 --> 00:03:30.614
I get my hot water.

00:03:30.614 --> 00:03:32.780
And, of course, I bring my
own teabag wherever I go.

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:35.640
Because you can't
trust the airport tea.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.660
And so I get my hot water.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:39.470
I get my tea.

00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:41.660
I set up this little
station for myself.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:44.030
And I'm like, ah,
writing about kale.

00:03:44.030 --> 00:03:45.800
This is so great.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:48.780
So like 5, 10 minutes go by.

00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:51.320
And all of a sudden, I
see people coming out

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:53.430
of this door in
this little section.

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:57.050
And I look up, and I see
it says, "Employees Only."

00:03:57.050 --> 00:03:58.820
So I'm in this
employees only section.

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:00.290
I didn't realize that I was.

00:04:00.290 --> 00:04:01.790
And I was like,
well, you know what?

00:04:01.790 --> 00:04:02.750
I'm not being bothered.

00:04:02.750 --> 00:04:04.060
To each his own.

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:06.080
It's all good.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:06.950
I'll just stay here.

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:10.160
If someone kicks me
out, it'll be fine.

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:12.501
So another like 5,
10 minutes go by.

00:04:12.501 --> 00:04:13.250
And this is early.

00:04:13.250 --> 00:04:15.320
This is like 7 o'clock
in the airport.

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:18.370
And all of a sudden,
this woman comes out

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:19.370
of this door, and this--

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:23.030
I'm going to do the best
impression of her that I can.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:23.651
She comes out.

00:04:23.651 --> 00:04:24.650
She's on her cell phone.

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:27.170
And she's like, I
hate this place!

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:28.600
This place sucks!

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:29.640
F you!

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:30.440
Bah!

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.630
And I'm like, oh, my goodness.

00:04:32.630 --> 00:04:34.880
I'm like, what is
wrong with this woman?

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:39.620
I'm like, does she not realize
I made a Feng shui thing here?

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:43.137
Like, this energy is just not
good for what I have going on.

00:04:43.137 --> 00:04:44.470
But she's just, like, miserable.

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:46.260
And she comes out of the
employee only section.

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:46.910
I'm like, whatever.

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:47.430
She left.

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:49.800
I was like, OK, you
know, to each his own.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:52.520
I'm going to go back
to writing about kale.

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:58.250
So another 5, 10 minutes go
by, and this woman comes back.

00:04:58.250 --> 00:05:01.930
And this time, she had
a tray full of food.

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:04.510
And of all the other nine tables
she could sit, where do you

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:06.870
think she sat?

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:09.130
Directly in front of me.

00:05:09.130 --> 00:05:12.150
But at this point, my computer
was blocking-- kind of

00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:13.856
like blocking her.

00:05:13.856 --> 00:05:16.230
But I'm sitting there, and
I'm like, she's in a bad mood.

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:18.672
She's miserable.

00:05:18.672 --> 00:05:20.880
I was like, I kind of want
to know what she's eating.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:23.130
Because remember, I cared.

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:24.255
I wanted to educate people.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:28.320
So I was like, should I look?

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:28.836
Shouldn't I?

00:05:28.836 --> 00:05:29.460
I was like, OK.

00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:30.360
I'm going to look
what she's eating.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:31.943
Because clearly she
was in a bad mood,

00:05:31.943 --> 00:05:33.840
and I need to see what's
going on with her.

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:35.370
So my computer's up, right?

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:36.720
And I can't really see.

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:38.405
So I'm like-- all of
a sudden, you just

00:05:38.405 --> 00:05:41.460
see my head peek
out from my computer

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:44.370
to try to get a glimpse
of what's on her tray.

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:47.130
And I could not make
this story up if I tried.

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:49.950
This was about 7:30
in the morning now.

00:05:49.950 --> 00:05:54.660
On her tray, this woman had a
large Ben and Jerry's chocolate

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:56.550
milkshake.

00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:59.160
Some people are like, oh,
isn't that considered kind

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:00.570
of a smoothie?

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:03.264
And I kind of want those
for breakfast myself.

00:06:03.264 --> 00:06:04.680
As if that wasn't
enough, she then

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:08.640
had a large bowl of chocolate
ice cream with whipped cream

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:11.820
on top, right next
to the milkshake.

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.010
As if that wasn't
enough, she then

00:06:14.010 --> 00:06:16.740
had a large omelette
with hash browns,

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:18.330
and she's just
pouring ketchup on it.

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:20.650
And this is at 7:30
in the morning.

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:25.140
And the health coach in
me is like, oh my god.

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:26.700
Does she not know
what she's doing?

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:28.170
Is she not knowing
that what she's eating

00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:29.836
is directly affecting
how she's feeling?

00:06:29.836 --> 00:06:31.890
And the reason why she
is coming out here,

00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:34.650
and she's so miserable,
and she's flipping out

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:36.150
is because of all this food?

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:38.562
And I was so angry with her.

00:06:38.562 --> 00:06:40.020
I was like, oh, I
want to tell her.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:42.370
I want to tell her that
there's more out there for her.

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:44.760
But I was like,
Lindsey, you're going

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:45.860
with your nutrition peeps.

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:48.330
You're going to be with
them in a couple hours.

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:49.314
Just calm down, relax.

00:06:49.314 --> 00:06:50.730
You're not trying
to get arrested.

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:52.420
So I was like, OK.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:55.080
So I put some of the essential
oils or something on me

00:06:55.080 --> 00:06:57.720
and was like, we're
going to calm down.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:02.430
So then, 5, 10 more minutes go
by, and I hear some shuffling.

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:03.930
And I'm like, do I look?

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:05.190
Don't I look?

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:07.560
But then I'm like, I'm
kind of already invested.

00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:08.920
I need to know what she's doing.

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:11.325
So again, peeking
around the computer.

00:07:11.325 --> 00:07:14.700
At, like, 7:35,
7:40 in the morning,

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:18.410
this woman now pulls
out a lunchbox cooler.

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:21.390
I'm like, are you kidding me?

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:22.140
More food?

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:23.370
What could you possibly need?

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:24.536
And then I'm calculating it.

00:07:24.536 --> 00:07:27.990
I'm like, you just ate 3,200
calories, 87 grams of sugar.

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:31.440
There's probably 87
chemicals in that milkshake.

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:34.110
And I'm getting so
upset with this woman.

00:07:34.110 --> 00:07:35.710
I'm like, uhh.

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:39.019
So I'm like, OK, calm down.

00:07:39.019 --> 00:07:40.810
But then she pulls out
her lunchbox cooler.

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:43.290
And I'm like, OK, I need
to see what she has in it.

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:46.800
And at like 7:40 in the morning,
this woman, on her tray,

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:50.700
pulls out five
prescription medications.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:53.220
And one by one, she's slurping
them down with her chocolate

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:54.350
milkshake.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:56.730
And at this point, I am
furious with this woman.

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:58.611
I'm like, oh my goodness.

00:07:58.611 --> 00:08:00.360
Do you not realize
that what you're eating

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:02.026
is directly affecting
how you're feeling

00:08:02.026 --> 00:08:03.750
and all of these medications--

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:06.540
you know, you wouldn't have
to take them if you would just

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:07.980
eat properly and--

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.087
you know, you-- oh, I
was just so frustrated.

00:08:10.087 --> 00:08:11.920
I could not believe
that this was happening.

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:15.930
So at this point, I
put my laptop down.

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:18.099
I'm just looking at
her like, it is on.

00:08:18.099 --> 00:08:20.390
But then I'm like, I'm not
really going to do anything.

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:23.850
[LAUGHS] But I was
like, it is on.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:26.370
And I just couldn't believe
that someone could do that

00:08:26.370 --> 00:08:30.300
to themselves, to eat
that way and then think

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:33.510
that the medication
was going to help.

00:08:33.510 --> 00:08:36.330
So at this point, I was really
engrossed in this woman.

00:08:36.330 --> 00:08:38.400
And I was just like, I
need to know everything

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:39.570
and what she's doing.

00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:42.059
But I was like, just calm down.

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:45.010
So I was trying to
calm myself down.

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:46.900
But I just kept staring at her.

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:48.930
And then five more
minutes go by,

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:50.940
and then this is when
everything changed.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:53.220
It's 7:30 in the airport.

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:56.020
And this woman pulls out her
lunchbox cooler once again.

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:57.720
And I'm like, more food?

00:08:57.720 --> 00:08:58.440
More drugs?

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:01.350
What could you possibly need?

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:08.450
And at 7:45 in the airport, this
woman sits back in her chair.

00:09:08.450 --> 00:09:10.880
She takes a sigh.

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:11.854
She looks at her food.

00:09:11.854 --> 00:09:12.770
She looks at the tray.

00:09:12.770 --> 00:09:15.430
She looks at the drugs.

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:19.650
And she looked
defeated, like the food,

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:23.190
and the drugs, and
all of that, just won.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:25.530
She pushes her tray forward.

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:27.966
She grabs her lunchbox
cooler once again.

00:09:27.966 --> 00:09:29.340
And in the middle
of the airport,

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.860
this woman opens up the cooler.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:34.680
She lifts up her shirt, she
rubs herself with alcohol,

00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:36.570
and she injects herself
with an insulin shot.

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:43.660
And at this point, I was no
longer mad at this woman.

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:47.420
I was no longer frustrated
with this woman.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:51.250
I really was able,
in that moment,

00:09:51.250 --> 00:09:53.860
to see a reflection
of my own self

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:58.150
and the trajectory of
the path that I was on.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:00.250
I thought, what if, at
the end or the beginning

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:01.750
of the day, this woman--

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:04.390
the only thing she had
to make her feel better

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:06.160
was that chocolate milkshake?

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:08.420
She clearly didn't like her job.

00:10:08.420 --> 00:10:11.970
She was irritated at
someone on the phone.

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:15.180
And what if that
was the only thing--

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:17.100
and if she was diagnosed
with something, being

00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:20.190
diagnosed with any disease--

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:22.590
and I know personally--

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:23.730
is a challenge.

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:27.100
And it's something that
you need to work through.

00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:30.060
And so when I
watched this woman,

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:33.630
I was at first so judgmental.

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:37.067
And I realized, you know,
she was no different than me

00:10:37.067 --> 00:10:38.400
and I was no different than her.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:43.950
The difference is I was able
to choose a different way

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.890
and to get on a healthier track.

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:49.750
Because when I was 12 years
old, I suffered from anxiety.

00:10:49.750 --> 00:10:51.660
I was actually
hospitalized at age 12.

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:55.950
I was taken out of
school, put IVs in my arm.

00:10:55.950 --> 00:11:00.900
And I too used food
to fill a comfort,

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:03.570
to fill a void that
I felt within myself,

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:05.900
my low self-esteem.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:08.640
And so when I watched
her, I realized

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:09.840
I was no different than her.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:12.590
And here I had been judging
people, judging my family,

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:17.550
judging my friends, judging this
stranger at the airport, when

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:22.470
really what I needed to start
to understand and foster

00:11:22.470 --> 00:11:24.870
was real empathy and meeting
people where they are.

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:26.280
Because we don't know.

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:28.350
We don't know someone's life.

00:11:28.350 --> 00:11:32.400
We don't know what
they're struggling with.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.680
And it's meeting them where
they are and actually listening.

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:38.910
So this moment actually
changed the entire trajectory

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:39.540
of my career.

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:43.942
Because I was this crazy
judgmental person when

00:11:43.942 --> 00:11:46.150
it came to food and nutrition,
thought I knew it all,

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:48.600
wanted to evangelize
everyone I met.

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:52.650
And what I realized is that
it's a lot deeper than that.

00:11:52.650 --> 00:11:54.234
And so today I want
to share with you

00:11:54.234 --> 00:11:55.650
some of these
principles that I've

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:57.220
learned, not only
in my own journey,

00:11:57.220 --> 00:12:00.810
but through working with
people, and through seminars,

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:01.620
and through--

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:04.770
just hearing people's stories
when it comes to food.

00:12:04.770 --> 00:12:09.210
And the first thing that I truly
believe when it comes to food

00:12:09.210 --> 00:12:13.950
is that we were born
emotional eaters.

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:16.830
And I know that's kind
of a bold statement.

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:19.650
Because so many of us, when we
think of emotionally eating,

00:12:19.650 --> 00:12:22.676
we think of the breakup
with the ice cream.

00:12:22.676 --> 00:12:24.300
Or we think of a
stressful day at work,

00:12:24.300 --> 00:12:27.510
and I want pizza, or
a burger, or fries.

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:29.550
And that is one aspect of it.

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:30.660
And it is a spectrum.

00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:34.940
But our true being
are emotional eaters.

00:12:34.940 --> 00:12:39.110
What does a baby, a newborn,
do when they're hungry?

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:40.820
They cry.

00:12:40.820 --> 00:12:43.280
What did I do yesterday
when I was hungry?

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:46.250
I cried.

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:47.720
We're no different from that.

00:12:47.720 --> 00:12:53.240
And so because I truly believe
that we're emotional eaters--

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:55.639
and I look at it as
really a positive thing.

00:12:55.639 --> 00:12:57.680
I look at it as something
that we can learn from,

00:12:57.680 --> 00:13:02.600
that we can foster that empathy
within others and in ourselves,

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:05.660
and learn more about ourselves
through realizing that.

00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:11.360
Which brings me to my next
point, which is listening,

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:13.040
listening to your body.

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:15.450
So many times, we--

00:13:15.450 --> 00:13:19.340
how many of us have ever
been on a diet before?

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:20.960
That's like everyone.

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:23.430
That's like 99.9% of
people in the world.

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.000
I really want to meet
the 0.01% person that's

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.950
never been on a diet.

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:30.122
But maybe you've done
the buddy system.

00:13:30.122 --> 00:13:31.580
How many of you
have done the buddy

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:34.540
system, where you're like,
yeah, we're doing this together?

00:13:34.540 --> 00:13:37.340
And we're going on this plan,
and it's going to be great.

00:13:37.340 --> 00:13:42.950
And so maybe it's a partner,
or a friend, or a coworker.

00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:45.470
And you decide to
get on this plan,

00:13:45.470 --> 00:13:46.820
and you're all jazzed about it.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.750
And you're checking
in with each other.

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:50.541
And you're like, yeah,
this is going great.

00:13:50.541 --> 00:13:51.620
And week 1, right?

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:53.120
Week 1 is the big week.

00:13:53.120 --> 00:13:55.829
It's like when you
start feeling better,

00:13:55.829 --> 00:13:56.870
and you can start seeing.

00:13:56.870 --> 00:14:00.380
And your friend is like,
oh, I'm just loving this.

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:01.200
This is so great.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:04.310
I think I just lost three
pant sizes in one week.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:05.430
This is incredible.

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:07.130
I have so much more energy.

00:14:07.130 --> 00:14:09.890
And you're on the
scale, like, oh, my god.

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:11.750
Did I just gain weight?

00:14:11.750 --> 00:14:13.040
Is that possible?

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:16.650
We're doing the
same exact thing!

00:14:16.650 --> 00:14:21.000
And that's because every
body is so different.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.360
And so I think that
it's great that there's

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.760
different diets and lifestyles.

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:27.200
But I think what
we need to do is

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:29.510
take that information from
it and learn to figure out

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:31.610
what our body needs
and what truly

00:14:31.610 --> 00:14:33.410
is going to fuel our body.

00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:35.460
Because they're
all so different.

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:37.340
A quick example of this.

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:39.270
When I first got into
health and nutrition,

00:14:39.270 --> 00:14:42.500
we learned all the dietary
theories that there are,

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:43.760
pretty much.

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:45.710
And there's a lot of them.

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:50.330
And I was really big
into the blood type

00:14:50.330 --> 00:14:52.430
diet and some different diets.

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:54.380
And I thought-- I was like, yes.

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:58.220
My body is meant
to be vegetarian.

00:14:58.220 --> 00:14:59.160
This is what it is.

00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:02.750
So I was a vegetarian for eight
years, and then I went vegan.

00:15:02.750 --> 00:15:06.510
And about six months into
it, I got really sick.

00:15:06.510 --> 00:15:08.510
I mean, I passed out
in the shower, sick.

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:11.030
And here I am this health
person, this health coach.

00:15:11.030 --> 00:15:14.210
So it's like, yes, I eat fruits
and veggies, and I'm so great.

00:15:14.210 --> 00:15:16.850
And here I was passing
out in my shower.

00:15:16.850 --> 00:15:17.720
And it was not--

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:19.430
it was not one, a good look.

00:15:19.430 --> 00:15:24.840
And two, it proved
against what I know now,

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:26.780
which is that we're
so bioindividual

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:28.560
and we're so all different.

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:33.020
And so when that happened,
I got really sick.

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:37.640
And then I was like, all of a
sudden, I was craving a burger.

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:38.690
That's all I wanted.

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:40.580
I was just like, I--

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:43.550
but my mind was so ingrained
in being in this one way,

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:46.127
not listening to my body,
being OK, this is what you are.

00:15:46.127 --> 00:15:47.210
This is what you're doing.

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:51.620
It almost became part of who
I was, that I was vegetarian.

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:55.450
It was my label that I wanted
to wear and let everyone know.

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.101
And I wasn't actually listening.

00:15:57.101 --> 00:15:59.600
And all of a sudden, I'm just
craving this and craving this.

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:02.810
So finally one day, I decided--

00:16:02.810 --> 00:16:03.560
I told my husband.

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:06.080
I was like, I think
I need a burger.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:07.670
Will you go with me?

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:08.880
It was a big deal.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:12.450
I was like, we need to make
sure that it's grass-fed.

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:15.770
I need to know the cow's name.

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:18.560
I was like, we've really
got to be OK with this.

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:19.440
He was so excited.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:20.190
He was like, yeah.

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:22.023
He's like, I can't wait
to get this on film.

00:16:22.023 --> 00:16:23.480
And I'm like, oh my god.

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:25.284
So we go to this joint.

00:16:25.284 --> 00:16:26.700
And I'm literally--
I kid you not.

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:30.022
I'm walking in like,
I hope no one sees me.

00:16:30.022 --> 00:16:30.980
If they know that I'm--

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:33.030
I'm just getting a
veggie burger, guys.

00:16:33.030 --> 00:16:36.950
And so I go, and I
order this cheeseburger.

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:39.440
And I eat it.

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:45.980
And I felt so much better,
instantly so much better.

00:16:45.980 --> 00:16:49.820
And what I realized is I
was definitely lacking iron.

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:53.780
There were certain things in
my diet that I wasn't getting

00:16:53.780 --> 00:16:54.650
and that I needed.

00:16:54.650 --> 00:16:58.610
And it was in that instance
that I was like, you know,

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:00.350
listening to your
body is so important.

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:02.100
Because we put
labels on everything.

00:17:02.100 --> 00:17:06.440
And we want to constantly label
things, including our diet,

00:17:06.440 --> 00:17:08.550
and put ourselves
in these boxes.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:09.740
But our bodies change.

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:12.650
Every six months, your
taste buds are changing.

00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:15.619
And your body is constantly
evolving, and adapting,

00:17:15.619 --> 00:17:16.740
and changing.

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:19.069
And so you need to
be open and to listen

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:23.140
so that you can really
see what your body needs.

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:26.660
And when it comes to cravings,
like that red meat craving--

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:29.450
oftentimes, we look also at
cravings as a really bad thing.

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:31.400
We're like, oh,
I'm craving this.

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:34.250
I'm so bad.

00:17:34.250 --> 00:17:36.170
Cravings are actually
the gatekeepers

00:17:36.170 --> 00:17:39.690
to let our bodies know
what they really need.

00:17:39.690 --> 00:17:42.340
And the more that you listen,
the more that you understand,

00:17:42.340 --> 00:17:47.190
and the more that you can truly
foster a closer relationship

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:50.130
with you and your body, you
won't ever have to diet again.

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:52.980
Because you'll know what
your body needs, when--

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:54.000
at what times.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.900
And you'll be able to
adapt, and flow, and change,

00:17:57.900 --> 00:18:05.230
rather than being so restrictive
and so intense about it.

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:10.180
So the next point, when it
comes to food, and mood,

00:18:10.180 --> 00:18:12.910
and emotions, and
this whole concept,

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:15.620
is not only listening
to your body,

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:18.310
but also feeling your feelings.

00:18:18.310 --> 00:18:20.620
So many of us--
the reason why we

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:25.390
are quick to grab a Snickers
bar, quick to grab chips,

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:28.150
or whatever it may be, is
because we don't actually

00:18:28.150 --> 00:18:32.350
stop and allow ourselves
to feel whatever feeling

00:18:32.350 --> 00:18:33.940
that we're feeling.

00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:36.400
And we're just quick to
go to the next thing.

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:39.090
A quick-- another
little story about this.

00:18:39.090 --> 00:18:42.160
This was in 2014.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:46.060
This one day, it was a
rainy Saturday afternoon.

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:50.080
And all of a sudden, I
got this intense craving

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:51.910
for a grilled cheese.

00:18:51.910 --> 00:18:55.000
And I'm not talking like
those highbrow grilled cheeses

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.810
from, like, San Francisco,
you know, where they're like--

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:02.230
have all these crazy ingredients
on them, and they're like $25.

00:19:02.230 --> 00:19:07.135
I'm talking I wanted Wonder
Bread with butter and Land

00:19:07.135 --> 00:19:08.080
O'Lakes cheese.

00:19:08.080 --> 00:19:09.750
That's what I wanted.

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:11.710
And so I almost--

00:19:11.710 --> 00:19:13.210
I had my keys in my hand.

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:14.610
I'm ready to go out the door.

00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:15.610
And then I just stopped.

00:19:15.610 --> 00:19:18.725
And I said, what's
actually going on here?

00:19:18.725 --> 00:19:20.350
Let me just sit with
this for a minute.

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:22.570
Let me just feel
this for a minute.

00:19:22.570 --> 00:19:27.760
And so what I had realized is
I had this moment of clarity

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:31.660
and this moment of being
able to feel what I actually

00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:32.350
was feeling.

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:33.370
And it was grief.

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:34.750
And it was sadness.

00:19:34.750 --> 00:19:39.160
Because my dad
passed away in 2012.

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:43.090
And when I was a kid on
rainy Saturday afternoons,

00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:44.920
he would make me
a grilled cheese,

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:51.220
and we would watch copious
amounts of "Unsolved

00:19:51.220 --> 00:19:54.850
Mysteries," which,
as a seven-year-old--

00:19:54.850 --> 00:19:56.350
I was like seven
at the time-- like,

00:19:56.350 --> 00:19:58.600
the parenting choice of
letting your child watch--

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:00.433
you know, that's besides
the point-- letting

00:20:00.433 --> 00:20:02.260
me watch "Unsolved Mysteries."

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:04.390
But the point is I was--
in that moment, when

00:20:04.390 --> 00:20:08.110
I was craving that grilled
cheese, the raininess,

00:20:08.110 --> 00:20:09.670
the Saturday
afternoon-- all of that

00:20:09.670 --> 00:20:12.562
brought the feeling
of being with my dad.

00:20:12.562 --> 00:20:14.020
And so that's what
I really wanted.

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:15.850
That's what I was
really missing.

00:20:15.850 --> 00:20:17.740
And so at that point,
I had a decision.

00:20:17.740 --> 00:20:19.698
I was like, well, I can
eat the grilled cheese,

00:20:19.698 --> 00:20:22.480
eat it, appreciate it I
can make an upgraded one.

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:25.870
I can-- but then
I was like, huh.

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:28.990
I wonder if "Unsolved Mysteries"
is anywhere online right now.

00:20:28.990 --> 00:20:31.330
And I did find it
on Amazon Prime.

00:20:31.330 --> 00:20:33.850
And I was like, I'm going to
watch "Unsolved Mysteries"

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:37.270
this rainy afternoon,
and really honor and feel

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:38.410
that feeling in that way.

00:20:38.410 --> 00:20:40.840
And let me just tell you,
"Unsolved Mysteries,"

00:20:40.840 --> 00:20:43.870
as an adult, is a horrible show.

00:20:43.870 --> 00:20:46.360
I was like, why was I
allowed to watch this?

00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:47.921
This is so bad.

00:20:47.921 --> 00:20:49.420
They actually do
these reenactments.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:50.294
It's the whole thing.

00:20:50.294 --> 00:20:52.560
I was like, oh, my goodness.

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:53.810
But it actually made me laugh.

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:56.710
And feeling that feeling
and going with that--

00:20:56.710 --> 00:20:59.950
it actually ended up
providing me with nutrients

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:03.640
and providing me with a sense
that the grilled cheese never

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:04.420
could.

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:08.130
And that's because I
allowed myself to feel.

00:21:08.130 --> 00:21:14.050
So listening to your body,
feeling your feelings--

00:21:14.050 --> 00:21:17.290
and, you know, the
last thing with this

00:21:17.290 --> 00:21:20.920
is to prescribe as necessary.

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:25.420
And what I mean by that
is food can greatly

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:27.790
help with your emotions.

00:21:27.790 --> 00:21:32.060
And your emotions can dictate
the food choices that you eat.

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:33.940
And so I think it's
important to understand

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:37.630
how both play into your life
so that you can truly see what

00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:39.460
you may need at certain times.

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:43.240
For example, in my new
book, "Eat Your Feelings,"

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:45.910
I actually map out some
of the different emotions.

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:49.780
So for example, if
you're sad, your body

00:21:49.780 --> 00:21:52.210
really wants serotonin.

00:21:52.210 --> 00:21:55.090
And it can find that
in carbs and sugar,

00:21:55.090 --> 00:21:57.190
basically, so pizza and cookies.

00:21:57.190 --> 00:22:01.810
So when we're sad, our initial
quick knee-jerk reaction

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:03.580
is to go to the
pizza and the cookies

00:22:03.580 --> 00:22:05.710
because it's going to
give us that quick fix.

00:22:05.710 --> 00:22:09.760
However, long term, what your
body needs-- like I said,

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:11.020
it wants the serotonin.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:15.800
And so incorporating foods
such as nuts and seeds--

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:18.280
is just one example
that actually help

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:20.470
your body produce serotonin--

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:24.340
can give you longer term
benefits, rather than

00:22:24.340 --> 00:22:25.540
that quick fix.

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:27.040
Some of the other
ones that I have--

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:31.270
if you're sad, if you're
stressed, grounding foods.

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:32.860
When you're stressed
out, usually it's

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:35.106
all in your head
and your upper body.

00:22:35.106 --> 00:22:36.730
And so eating foods
that are grounding,

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:38.938
that are lower to the Earth,
can actually help ground

00:22:38.938 --> 00:22:42.906
you, so things like
carrots and sweet potatoes.

00:22:42.906 --> 00:22:44.030
So if you're sad, stressed.

00:22:44.030 --> 00:22:47.620
If you're tired, you
want something energizing

00:22:47.620 --> 00:22:51.100
and uplifting, so
citrus, or leafy greens,

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:52.790
or something like that.

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:55.740
And if you're
hangry, when you're

00:22:55.740 --> 00:23:00.140
so hungry that you become
angry, like I do, many days--

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:01.290
I always say that.

00:23:01.290 --> 00:23:04.410
You don't care if it was made
by Julia Child or a child,

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:06.180
you just need food
and need it now.

00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:08.820
So to avoid being
hangry, though, you

00:23:08.820 --> 00:23:12.030
