And so I think there's a
balance of something like that,

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:13.870
when you want a craving.

00:34:13.870 --> 00:34:17.860
And then also thinking of
this as preventative as well.

00:34:17.860 --> 00:34:19.871
By eating more of those
foods, it's called--

00:34:19.871 --> 00:34:21.370
what we learned in
nutrition school,

00:34:21.370 --> 00:34:22.578
which is called crowding out.

00:34:25.389 --> 00:34:28.510
So if you find yourself really
struggling with depression

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.082
or anxiety, and you start
incorporating more foods,

00:34:31.082 --> 00:34:32.540
it's not going to
happen overnight.

00:34:32.540 --> 00:34:34.540
But over time, what happens
is the more that you

00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:38.980
eat those foods, it naturally
crowds out the other thing.

00:34:38.980 --> 00:34:40.900
People ask me all
the time, Lindsey,

00:34:40.900 --> 00:34:43.448
how do you just have a piece of
dark chocolate and you're OK?

00:34:43.448 --> 00:34:44.739
Or you don't want these things?

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:46.239
I don't feel like
I'm depriving myself.

00:34:46.239 --> 00:34:47.863
But naturally, just
the way that I've--

00:34:47.863 --> 00:34:49.270
I've been doing
this work since I

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:51.880
was 12 years old, since
I suffered from anxiety

00:34:51.880 --> 00:34:53.500
and started to get help.

00:34:53.500 --> 00:34:55.840
And the first thing I did
was go to a wellness center

00:34:55.840 --> 00:34:57.130
in my hometown.

00:34:57.130 --> 00:35:02.186
And through that experience,
I started learning

00:35:02.186 --> 00:35:03.310
about health and nutrition.

00:35:03.310 --> 00:35:05.670
And so this has been
over half my life.

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:08.470
And so being easy
on yourself as well,

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:10.222
but also looking
at it as OK, I'm

00:35:10.222 --> 00:35:11.680
going to start
eating more of these

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:14.420
to naturally crowd out more
of those other cravings.

00:35:14.420 --> 00:35:17.320
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:20.150
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: That's
just such a fair point.

00:35:20.150 --> 00:35:22.850
We all are constantly
beating ourselves up.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:25.150
And I know you've written
quite a bit about food guilt.

00:35:25.150 --> 00:35:26.900
LINDSEY SMITH: Um-hmm,
my whole last book.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:28.335
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: It
was all about food guilt.

00:35:28.335 --> 00:35:28.630
LINDSEY SMITH: Yeah.

00:35:28.630 --> 00:35:29.750
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: But I
think since that came up,

00:35:29.750 --> 00:35:31.966
can you talk to us a
little bit about what

00:35:31.966 --> 00:35:33.590
you recommend for
people who are trying

00:35:33.590 --> 00:35:35.187
to get out of that cycle?

00:35:35.187 --> 00:35:36.020
LINDSEY SMITH: Yeah.

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:39.680
So I did a survey
with the Nielsen group

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:44.210
and found that 85% of
women and 65% of men

00:35:44.210 --> 00:35:45.985
experience food guilt
on a daily basis.

00:35:45.985 --> 00:35:47.360
And so I was
thinking about that.

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:49.760
And I'm like, going in--
what are they called, MKs?

00:35:49.760 --> 00:35:50.240
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: Um-hmm.

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:51.823
LINDSEY SMITH: OK,
going into the MK--

00:35:51.823 --> 00:35:52.820
I'm learning the lingo.

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:56.930
Going into the MKs over there.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:00.550
Or into your pantry, into your
fridge, out at a restaurant.

00:36:00.550 --> 00:36:04.370
85% of the time,
women, specifically,

00:36:04.370 --> 00:36:07.730
are feeling guilty, are
feeling stressed about food.

00:36:07.730 --> 00:36:11.130
And like I said, that is
causing stress on your body.

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:13.680
You're not able to
digest things as well.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:18.380
So part of that is being able
to go into every situation.

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:20.400
I always say, go into
every situation with food,

00:36:20.400 --> 00:36:23.570
whether it's kale or a
cookie, with a sense of love

00:36:23.570 --> 00:36:25.220
and appreciation for that.

00:36:25.220 --> 00:36:29.145
I had a client once, and
I was teaching her this.

00:36:29.145 --> 00:36:30.770
And the one day,
she's like, Lindsey, I

00:36:30.770 --> 00:36:32.930
was craving a
McDonald's cheeseburger.

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:36.100
And I was like, OK,
what did you do?

00:36:36.100 --> 00:36:37.120
I wanted to know.

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:40.750
And she was like, well,
I was beating myself up,

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:42.387
but I was going to
go get it anyway,

00:36:42.387 --> 00:36:43.970
but then I was doing
that whole thing.

00:36:43.970 --> 00:36:45.020
But then I remembered
what you said.

00:36:45.020 --> 00:36:46.561
So I was like, OK,
I'm going to allow

00:36:46.561 --> 00:36:48.230
myself to go there, to do this.

00:36:48.230 --> 00:36:51.730
She was like, so I
went, I ordered it.

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:55.220
I was real nice to
the drive-thru people,

00:36:55.220 --> 00:36:57.080
and I was like, thank you.

00:36:57.080 --> 00:36:58.670
And I go and pull over.

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:01.490
And she's like, and I sit
there with my hamburger,

00:37:01.490 --> 00:37:04.610
and I'm just like thinking
about the whole process

00:37:04.610 --> 00:37:05.990
this hamburger took to get here.

00:37:05.990 --> 00:37:08.950
I was like, wow, the
farms that had this wheat

00:37:08.950 --> 00:37:10.490
to make this bun.

00:37:10.490 --> 00:37:11.240
And she was like--

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:12.740
I mean, she was
really going for it.

00:37:12.740 --> 00:37:14.892
And she was like, I
stopped and appreciated it.

00:37:14.892 --> 00:37:16.600
She's like, and then
I ate the hamburger.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:17.650
And she's like, and guess what?

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:18.420
I was like, what?

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:19.970
And she's like, I
didn't get sick.

00:37:19.970 --> 00:37:20.990
She's like, normally,
I would get sick.

00:37:20.990 --> 00:37:22.954
She's like, but I ate
a McDonald's hamburger,

00:37:22.954 --> 00:37:23.870
and I didn't get sick.

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:24.870
So I'm a little worried.

00:37:27.650 --> 00:37:30.050
What she did is she was
like, and then I did it,

00:37:30.050 --> 00:37:33.057
and I let it go, and it
didn't sit with me for weeks.

00:37:33.057 --> 00:37:34.640
I wasn't constantly
thinking about it.

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:37.010
And she's like, to be
honest, it didn't even

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:38.457
do what it normally did for me.

00:37:38.457 --> 00:37:40.290
Because now I'm at the
point where I'm like,

00:37:40.290 --> 00:37:43.160
OK, I don't feel
that like I need it

00:37:43.160 --> 00:37:45.710
or that it's going to
provide me with something.

00:37:45.710 --> 00:37:49.160
Because I've been able to
just see it for what it is

00:37:49.160 --> 00:37:51.440
and not make it a
bigger production

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:55.730
or bring more emotional
value than what it really is.

00:37:55.730 --> 00:37:58.940
And oftentimes, we do that,
because food is very emotional.

00:37:58.940 --> 00:38:01.750
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: Yeah,
that makes a ton of sense.

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:03.353
Any live questions?

00:38:03.353 --> 00:38:04.677
Yeah, go for it.

00:38:04.677 --> 00:38:05.510
LINDSEY SMITH: More.

00:38:05.510 --> 00:38:07.990
Woo.

00:38:07.990 --> 00:38:09.720
AUDIENCE: So when
you have craving,

00:38:09.720 --> 00:38:11.450
when do you know you
should go for it,

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:12.947
or when should you hold back?

00:38:12.947 --> 00:38:14.530
LINDSEY SMITH: That's
a good question.

00:38:14.530 --> 00:38:16.590
I would say, you're
probably going

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:18.510
to not like me for this answer.

00:38:18.510 --> 00:38:22.230
But I would say, I think
you really have to--

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:24.390
that's when it comes to
listening to your body

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:29.370
and being able to decipher
some of the differences.

00:38:29.370 --> 00:38:35.290
And I think it's not going
to come by being perfect.

00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:38.830
It's going to come from giving
in to a craving and being like,

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:40.770
oh, I didn't feel that
great because of it.

00:38:40.770 --> 00:38:46.770
Or it's not even giving in,
allowing yourself to go for it

00:38:46.770 --> 00:38:48.960
and then seeing how you
feel in that moment.

00:38:48.960 --> 00:38:52.890
And taking all of
this as information,

00:38:52.890 --> 00:38:55.630
thinking a bit like a Google
search, except for your body.

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:56.790
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE:
Ooh, there you go.

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:58.050
LINDSEY SMITH: Look at that.

00:38:58.050 --> 00:39:00.480
I'm just really
cheesing it up today.

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:04.107
But thinking of it as like
a search that's like, OK,

00:39:04.107 --> 00:39:05.190
this works or this didn't.

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:06.898
And asking yourself
the deeper questions,

00:39:06.898 --> 00:39:09.510
like, OK, well, why
am I craving this?

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:11.560
Is there something
happening today?

00:39:11.560 --> 00:39:13.400
What's my stress level like?

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:19.380
And I even map out in the
book some different questions.

00:39:19.380 --> 00:39:20.610
Let me see where they're at--

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:22.230
different questions
to ask yourself

00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:25.860
when you are feeling
like you want

00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:33.817
to have something to really
kind of stop and ask yourself.

00:39:33.817 --> 00:39:34.900
I can't find it right now.

00:39:34.900 --> 00:39:36.600
But it's in here.

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:40.960
The other thing that I
just noticed here too, is--

00:39:40.960 --> 00:39:44.181
I'm like, look at what
I notice in my own book.

00:39:44.181 --> 00:39:46.170
But the other thing
that I noticed

00:39:46.170 --> 00:39:50.520
is sometimes, part
of my method and my--

00:39:50.520 --> 00:39:54.310
in this book, specifically--
is going deeper.

00:39:54.310 --> 00:39:58.080
But then also saying,
OK, I'm craving sugar.

00:39:58.080 --> 00:39:59.130
I'm craving this.

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:00.960
And then I have a
chart in here that says

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:03.240
what your body may really need.

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:04.995
And so you'll be able
to start putting--

00:40:04.995 --> 00:40:06.870
it's like putting the
puzzle pieces together.

00:40:06.870 --> 00:40:10.090
You do the searches and
then you start mapping out.

00:40:10.090 --> 00:40:13.290
And you're like, oh, so for
me, if I'm craving a burger,

00:40:13.290 --> 00:40:19.400
I know that it's probably
that time, people, and my iron

00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:23.290
is getting low, and that's
just what my body needs.

00:40:23.290 --> 00:40:26.380
And so I know how
to fuel it properly.

00:40:26.380 --> 00:40:29.690
But it didn't always
come that way.

00:40:29.690 --> 00:40:33.634
So I think that can help.

00:40:33.634 --> 00:40:36.050
AUDIENCE: What's your approach
to influencing your friends

00:40:36.050 --> 00:40:39.410
and family to eat healthier
without becoming that person?

00:40:39.410 --> 00:40:40.580
LINDSEY SMITH: Ooh!

00:40:40.580 --> 00:40:43.190
Girl.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:47.930
So my approach is just
having empathy for people,

00:40:47.930 --> 00:40:49.640
trying to meet people
where they're at.

00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:52.790
When my dad got sick in 2000--

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:57.320
2010, I believe,
I was like, Dad,

00:40:57.320 --> 00:40:58.880
we need to be
doing ginger shots.

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:01.830
And I was telling
him all these things.

00:41:01.830 --> 00:41:05.360
And what I realized
is that I had

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:07.520
to meet him where he was at.

00:41:07.520 --> 00:41:11.870
He was a drinker, and a
smoker, and loves McDonald's.

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:13.760
I'm not going to--

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:18.361
this man is not going to
start doing ginger shots.

00:41:18.361 --> 00:41:20.360
So then what I did is I
met him where he was at.

00:41:20.360 --> 00:41:22.640
I was like, Dad, I bet you
can't do this ginger shot.

00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:24.830
Since he was a
drinker, I was like--

00:41:24.830 --> 00:41:26.509
I like masked them
and was like, I

00:41:26.509 --> 00:41:28.050
bet this would be
too strong for you.

00:41:28.050 --> 00:41:29.133
I know you're a vodka guy.

00:41:29.133 --> 00:41:31.490
But this ginger is even
stronger than vodka, Dad.

00:41:31.490 --> 00:41:33.570
And so it became kind of a joke.

00:41:33.570 --> 00:41:35.990
But I think meeting
people where they're at.

00:41:35.990 --> 00:41:38.660
I think one of the
things that I try to do

00:41:38.660 --> 00:41:42.500
is just have that empathy for
people and try to foster that.

00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:46.490
Because I have never
really met anyone

00:41:46.490 --> 00:41:49.700
that got healthier
because of judgments.

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:54.350
And if anything, it leads
to horrible eating cycles

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:55.610
over time.

00:41:55.610 --> 00:41:57.170
So something that
I try to do is just

00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:01.280
be the example myself
and bring things.

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:03.680
Bring a certain salad, or
a certain dish, or a bread,

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:04.760
and let them try it.

00:42:04.760 --> 00:42:08.540
And my mom had never
tried hummus before.

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:10.340
And I brought it.

00:42:10.340 --> 00:42:11.780
And now she's like, oh--

00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:12.494
sorry.

00:42:12.494 --> 00:42:14.660
I'm from Pittsburgh, so
when I talk about my parents

00:42:14.660 --> 00:42:15.770
I do the Yinzer accent.

00:42:15.770 --> 00:42:17.030
And it just almost came out.

00:42:17.030 --> 00:42:20.150
Because we call ourselves--
people say yinz instead of you

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:21.200
guys or y'all.

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:21.800
We say yinz.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:23.670
So my mom's like,
oh, I just loved it.

00:42:23.670 --> 00:42:28.065
Oh, I just loved that
hummus that yinz got.

00:42:28.065 --> 00:42:28.940
That's how they talk.

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:34.637
And then my father-in-law
the one day--

00:42:34.637 --> 00:42:35.720
he knows that I'm in this.

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:37.580
And this was so sweet.

00:42:37.580 --> 00:42:40.254
He was like, Linds,
I got that quinoa

00:42:40.254 --> 00:42:41.420
that you were talking about.

00:42:41.420 --> 00:42:44.540
And I was like, you mean quinoa?

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:46.220
But it showed that
they were interested.

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:48.360
And it was because this
is the way that I live.

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:49.985
And I'm not going to
try to change you,

00:42:49.985 --> 00:42:52.100
but I will bring
something so that you

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:54.050
can try it and enjoy it too.

00:42:54.050 --> 00:42:57.050
And so I think, with that, I've
seen changes in my own family

00:42:57.050 --> 00:42:59.660
members through just
leading by example

00:42:59.660 --> 00:43:02.905
and not being judgmental.

00:43:02.905 --> 00:43:04.280
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE:
That's huge.

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:06.560
I love your point about
people don't change

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:08.282
because they feel judged.

00:43:08.282 --> 00:43:10.490
They're going to change when
they're ready to change.

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:11.573
LINDSEY SMITH: Absolutely.

00:43:11.573 --> 00:43:16.220
And when I was the judgmental
person, everyone just hated me.

00:43:16.220 --> 00:43:17.990
In fact, my friends
have a running joke.

00:43:17.990 --> 00:43:19.739
They were like, yeah,
remember that period

00:43:19.739 --> 00:43:22.730
where we all stopped
talking to you.

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:24.880
I'm like, those are great times.

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:27.800
I was like, but at
least I had kale.

00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:33.172
it's just because that's
just not how we thrive.

00:43:33.172 --> 00:43:34.130
Now, some people maybe.

00:43:34.130 --> 00:43:34.730
But I doubt it.

00:43:34.730 --> 00:43:36.260
It's probably a very
small percentage.

00:43:36.260 --> 00:43:38.009
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE:
Yeah, I would say so.

00:43:41.164 --> 00:43:41.705
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:41.705 --> 00:43:43.000
I have a question.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.730
For all these fad
diets, which ones do you

00:43:45.730 --> 00:43:49.450
find the most misleading or--

00:43:49.450 --> 00:43:51.550
dangerous is too
extreme of a word--

00:43:51.550 --> 00:43:56.260
and which ones do you see as
healthier options and ones

00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:59.507
that you can incorporate along
with your daily nutrition?

00:43:59.507 --> 00:44:00.340
LINDSEY SMITH: Yeah.

00:44:00.340 --> 00:44:01.370
That's a good question.

00:44:01.370 --> 00:44:06.280
I think that the ones that
I hate the most personally

00:44:06.280 --> 00:44:10.150
are the click bait
things that are like,

00:44:10.150 --> 00:44:13.000
the five fruits that
are ruining your life.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.637
And I'm like, but it's fruit.

00:44:15.637 --> 00:44:17.470
You know, there's like,
why you should never

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:19.360
have a banana ever again.

00:44:19.360 --> 00:44:21.947
And I'm like, but it's a fruit.

00:44:21.947 --> 00:44:23.530
And I think that
that's where it comes

00:44:23.530 --> 00:44:25.970
to listening to your body,
because then-- some people,

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:27.440
yeah, a banana is great.

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:31.340
Some people-- it may
not sit well with you.

00:44:31.340 --> 00:44:33.160
So those are the ones
that I don't like.

00:44:33.160 --> 00:44:40.330
If anything is too restrictive,
over time, it's not feasible.

00:44:40.330 --> 00:44:43.480
So if something is too--

00:44:43.480 --> 00:44:45.094
I know a lot of people--

00:44:45.094 --> 00:44:47.260
some of these people are
my friends that have these,

00:44:47.260 --> 00:44:49.010
so I don't want
to call them out.

00:44:49.010 --> 00:44:52.480
But there's certain
trends, there's certain--

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:58.810
like diet programs that
come around every year.

00:44:58.810 --> 00:45:04.170
And I think the
problem with them

00:45:04.170 --> 00:45:07.530
is that they're so
restrictive that long term,

00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:09.957
it's hard for that to
become a lifestyle.

00:45:09.957 --> 00:45:11.540
Because then we carry
the guilt in it.

00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:13.860
We're like, well,
I'm not doing--

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:18.110
oh, I want grains now, or
I want something now, then.

00:45:18.110 --> 00:45:20.830
And I can't have it.

00:45:20.830 --> 00:45:21.810
So I think that.

00:45:21.810 --> 00:45:26.040
I think the biggest thing
is more plant based.

00:45:26.040 --> 00:45:28.680
We can all afford to
eat more plant based.

00:45:28.680 --> 00:45:32.400
I think that's one thing
that I can get behind,

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:34.800
just because we should
all be eating more fruits

00:45:34.800 --> 00:45:36.240
or vegetables anyway.

00:45:36.240 --> 00:45:38.580
So incorporating more
plant based foods

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:42.060
into your lifestyle, I think, is
one that'll never really go out

00:45:42.060 --> 00:45:44.769
of style because of that.

00:45:44.769 --> 00:45:46.560
But it really just
comes down to listening.

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:51.540
Because you can do any of those
types of diets and see what

00:45:51.540 --> 00:45:52.770
feels best for you.

00:45:52.770 --> 00:45:55.800
So if you're doing paleo,
that may work really well,

00:45:55.800 --> 00:45:57.430
and you may say yes.

00:45:57.430 --> 00:45:58.860
And it can change.

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:02.100
I didn't eat poultry
for 10 years.

00:46:02.100 --> 00:46:05.460
And this past September,
all in one day,

00:46:05.460 --> 00:46:07.950
I was like, I just need a
whole chicken right now.

00:46:07.950 --> 00:46:09.180
And I don't know.

00:46:09.180 --> 00:46:09.930
And you know what?

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:12.610
It was my collagen.

00:46:12.610 --> 00:46:15.240
I needed more
collagen in my joints.

00:46:15.240 --> 00:46:18.000
And I was eating chicken,
and I was like, fine.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.560
My joints felt so much better.

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:23.280
And so it can change.

00:46:23.280 --> 00:46:27.120
And being open to that, and
taking what you learn from it,

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:28.570
and going from there.

00:46:28.570 --> 00:46:29.410
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE:
So I have a question.

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:30.201
LINDSEY SMITH: Yes.

00:46:30.201 --> 00:46:33.090
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: I work
with a lot of women who suffer

00:46:33.090 --> 00:46:35.100
or have suffered from
eating disorders.

00:46:35.100 --> 00:46:38.430
So listening to their bodies
is really, really hard.

00:46:38.430 --> 00:46:40.500
What recommendations
do you have for people

00:46:40.500 --> 00:46:42.480
who are just getting
started on that journey

00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:45.960
and maybe don't even
know what that means?

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:48.030
LINDSEY SMITH: I think
paying attention.

00:46:48.030 --> 00:46:49.609
And I also think
finding support,

00:46:49.609 --> 00:46:51.150
you know, like
someone like yourself,

00:46:51.150 --> 00:46:54.840
or just being able to
have someone that you

00:46:54.840 --> 00:46:56.400
can talk to about these things.

00:46:56.400 --> 00:46:59.820
Because I think sometimes
talking through things

00:46:59.820 --> 00:47:04.290
can help you realize,
oh, yeah, this

00:47:04.290 --> 00:47:07.071
is why I did this or
this is why I did that.

00:47:07.071 --> 00:47:09.570
And being able to have that
kind of sounding board, I think,

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:10.750
is really important.

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:14.190
And then I think for anyone
just starting with the basics,

00:47:14.190 --> 00:47:17.040
doing one thing a week for
yourself and your health.

00:47:17.040 --> 00:47:20.870
So many times we're like, I'm
going to the grocery store.

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:22.620
I'm getting all the
fruits and vegetables.

00:47:22.620 --> 00:47:24.400
I have meal plans for days.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:27.032
I've got breakfast, lunch,
and dinner planned out.

00:47:27.032 --> 00:47:28.490
And then by Wednesday,
you're like,

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:30.600
oh, I just want a burger
from the local joint

00:47:30.600 --> 00:47:32.520
down the street.

00:47:32.520 --> 00:47:35.510
Or half your groceries
just end up sitting there.

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:38.010
You don't eat them because it's
not what your body is really

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:38.590
wanting.

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:41.320
And so instead of going
all in, I just tell people,

00:47:41.320 --> 00:47:42.660
hey, do one thing a week.

00:47:42.660 --> 00:47:44.950
Drink more water.

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:45.630
It's simple.

00:47:45.630 --> 00:47:47.110
We don't do it, include myself.

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:51.490
I'm like, I need to start
hydrating this trip.

00:47:51.490 --> 00:47:53.345
But just doing simple things.

00:47:53.345 --> 00:47:55.470
And over time, it just
becomes part of who you are.

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:56.580
And then the awareness.

00:47:56.580 --> 00:48:00.510
Because some people are at a
point where, like you said,

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:03.510
they're so conflicted
with all these things.

00:48:03.510 --> 00:48:05.760
The other day I went
in a grocery store,

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:10.120
and there was half
the fat avocados.

00:48:10.120 --> 00:48:12.380
I was like, what?

00:48:12.380 --> 00:48:13.880
That's how they
were marketing them.

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:15.890
And I'm like, half
the fat avoc--

00:48:15.890 --> 00:48:17.770
just eat the avocado.

00:48:17.770 --> 00:48:20.910
And all it was was an
avocado cut in half.

00:48:20.910 --> 00:48:23.640
That's all it was.

00:48:23.640 --> 00:48:26.290
It was just packaged like that,
like it's now half the fat.

00:48:26.290 --> 00:48:30.010
I'm like, yeah, I can go get
one off the bin over here

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:31.405
for $3 less.

00:48:34.669 --> 00:48:36.710
But being bombarded with
that stuff all the time,

00:48:36.710 --> 00:48:37.790
especially with an
eating disorder,

00:48:37.790 --> 00:48:38.870
can be very sensitive.

00:48:38.870 --> 00:48:41.860
And so I think seeking support
and then starting small

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:45.740
and being OK with yourself--
or not OK with yourself,

00:48:45.740 --> 00:48:50.170
but being OK with
starting small.

00:48:50.170 --> 00:48:51.960
Because it's hard
for a lot of people.

00:48:51.960 --> 00:48:53.190
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE:
Yeah, thank you.

00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:54.310
We have another live question.

00:48:54.310 --> 00:48:54.790
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:54.790 --> 00:48:55.270
LINDSEY SMITH: Hi.

00:48:55.270 --> 00:48:57.436
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
suggestions for situations

00:48:57.436 --> 00:48:59.740
where you can't really
control your food?

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:00.910
I'm also from Pennsylvania.

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:02.269
So when I go home, it's like--

00:49:02.269 --> 00:49:03.310
LINDSEY SMITH: What part?

00:49:03.310 --> 00:49:04.870
AUDIENCE: Northeast.

00:49:04.870 --> 00:49:05.460
Scranton.

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:06.710
LINDSEY SMITH: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:49:06.710 --> 00:49:08.300
AUDIENCE: So my mom
will be like, hey,

00:49:08.300 --> 00:49:10.030
I know you like
avocado and kale now.

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:13.119
But here she bakes a pizza and a
dozen cupcakes for the two days

00:49:13.119 --> 00:49:13.660
you are here.

00:49:16.310 --> 00:49:18.556
LINDSEY SMITH: So a couple
of my own personal tricks.

00:49:18.556 --> 00:49:20.180
I don't know if this
will work for you.

00:49:20.180 --> 00:49:24.340
But I just tend to
bring snacks and bring--

00:49:24.340 --> 00:49:26.250
so if I was going home,
I'd be like, oh, I'm

00:49:26.250 --> 00:49:29.170
going to stop and
get some whatever.

00:49:29.170 --> 00:49:32.440
And then you'd get something
healthy and bring it to share.

00:49:32.440 --> 00:49:34.780
I'm always big into like
bringing things to share,

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:38.260
and selfishly, because
I want to know what

00:49:38.260 --> 00:49:39.940
I'm walking into a little bit.

00:49:42.829 --> 00:49:45.370
And also, if there's something
that you want when you're home

00:49:45.370 --> 00:49:49.330
or where it's hard,
I think it's just

00:49:49.330 --> 00:49:52.210
going back to being mindful
of not beating yourself up

00:49:52.210 --> 00:49:56.320
being like OK, this is
two days we're here.

00:49:56.320 --> 00:49:58.040
I brought these
snacks, and we're good.

00:49:58.040 --> 00:50:00.820
But I know my mom really wants
to go to this pizza joint

00:50:00.820 --> 00:50:02.110
because it means a lot to her.

00:50:02.110 --> 00:50:04.557
And this is her way
of showing love,

00:50:04.557 --> 00:50:06.640
so I'm going to just
appreciate it for what it is.

00:50:06.640 --> 00:50:09.410
And being kind of a little
bit easy on yourself.

00:50:09.410 --> 00:50:11.320
And I think that'll
help you actually feel--

00:50:11.320 --> 00:50:13.861
you'll probably feel
less anxious going home.

00:50:13.861 --> 00:50:16.360
Because you probably already
pre-worry about that before you

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:17.980
go home.

00:50:17.980 --> 00:50:20.830
So I think that'll help you
ease into it a little bit more.

00:50:20.830 --> 00:50:24.250
And just give yourself some
grace and empathy as well.

00:50:24.250 --> 00:50:30.190
Because we tend to just beat
ourselves up before anything.

00:50:30.190 --> 00:50:32.990
We pre-worry about food
more than I have ever.

00:50:32.990 --> 00:50:35.251
And even myself,
I'm like, oh, am I

00:50:35.251 --> 00:50:37.000
going to know what I
eat when I get there?

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:38.860
It's like this thing.

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:44.020
But I think controlling what you
can, but then giving yourself

00:50:44.020 --> 00:50:47.246
grace moving forward,
if that makes sense.

00:50:47.246 --> 00:50:48.710
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:50:48.710 --> 00:50:49.870
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: Any
other live questions?

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:51.245
Otherwise, we have
a few minutes,

00:50:51.245 --> 00:50:55.300
and I want to tackle
one more Dory question.

00:50:55.300 --> 00:50:57.290
So I love the question
about anxiety.

00:50:57.290 --> 00:51:01.300
So what other things did you do
to help overcome your anxiety?

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:03.940
And if you still get anxious
today, how do you cope with it?

00:51:03.940 --> 00:51:04.731
LINDSEY SMITH: Yes.

00:51:04.731 --> 00:51:06.550
So I definitely
still get anxious.

00:51:06.550 --> 00:51:09.500
I'm not perfect.

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:11.940
One of the things
when I was a kid--

00:51:11.940 --> 00:51:13.440
and I don't think
I mentioned this--

00:51:13.440 --> 00:51:15.370
but I suffered from anxiety.

00:51:15.370 --> 00:51:16.520
I was hospitalized.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:20.450
And I was kind of
intuitive as a kid,

00:51:20.450 --> 00:51:23.870
and I think which leads to the
approach that I take today,

00:51:23.870 --> 00:51:25.730
because I've tapped into that.

00:51:25.730 --> 00:51:30.350
But I said to my parents,
I was like, you know what?

00:51:30.350 --> 00:51:32.840
I don't want to
continue this way.

00:51:32.840 --> 00:51:34.850
This is not being--

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:37.481
going to the hospital,
like all this, this isn't--

00:51:37.481 --> 00:51:38.480
I don't want to do this.

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:40.340
So do you think I
could try something?

00:51:40.340 --> 00:51:41.210
Could I get therapy?

00:51:41.210 --> 00:51:43.187
So my parents were like,
yeah, cool, whatever.

00:51:43.187 --> 00:51:44.270
We'll take you to therapy.

00:51:44.270 --> 00:51:45.197
I'm like, great.

00:51:45.197 --> 00:51:47.030
They've never been to
therapy in their life,

00:51:47.030 --> 00:51:48.405
but they're like,
sure, whatever,

00:51:48.405 --> 00:51:50.090
which I was grateful for.

00:51:50.090 --> 00:51:52.580
So I started going to
therapy, and it was OK.

00:51:52.580 --> 00:51:57.020
But my therapist was old school,
so it was very straightforward,

00:51:57.020 --> 00:51:58.110
like OK.

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:00.560
And as you can tell, I'm wearing
a fruit and veggies suit.

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:02.060
I like to keep it
a little bit real.

00:52:06.957 --> 00:52:08.540
My sister's eight
years older than me.

00:52:08.540 --> 00:52:10.580
And she started going
to this wellness center,

00:52:10.580 --> 00:52:12.590
and I saw a shift in her.

00:52:12.590 --> 00:52:14.040
We suffered from similar things.

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:16.099
And I said, hey, can
I try that instead?

00:52:16.099 --> 00:52:17.390
So they were like, sure, great.

00:52:17.390 --> 00:52:19.760
So I started going to
this wellness center.

00:52:19.760 --> 00:52:24.630
And we really focused
on eating mindfulness.

00:52:24.630 --> 00:52:29.210
He taught me Tai chi,
actually, as a 12-year-old.

00:52:29.210 --> 00:52:30.350
Yeah, I know.

00:52:30.350 --> 00:52:33.740
Acupuncture-- I was
doing all of it.

00:52:33.740 --> 00:52:37.610
And those things
really helped me.

00:52:37.610 --> 00:52:39.440
And by ninth grade,
I was actually

00:52:39.440 --> 00:52:43.490
teaching stress management
workshops to my student council

00:52:43.490 --> 00:52:44.810
conferences.

00:52:44.810 --> 00:52:47.100
Because I learned all
these different tools.

00:52:47.100 --> 00:52:49.740
So I definitely think
that food is a part of it.

00:52:49.740 --> 00:52:52.370
I know what foods can trigger
me and can trigger anxiety

00:52:52.370 --> 00:52:53.780
within me.

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:57.660
But then sometimes,
I get anxiety.

00:52:57.660 --> 00:52:59.850
And I'm like, I
didn't eat anything,

00:52:59.850 --> 00:53:02.850
I don't even feel
stressed in my mind.

00:53:02.850 --> 00:53:04.500
But my body is anxious.

00:53:04.500 --> 00:53:10.080
And so for me, a lot of times
it has to do with taking less

00:53:10.080 --> 00:53:13.560
screen time-- which I know is
not something Googlers want

00:53:13.560 --> 00:53:15.360
to hear--

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:18.972
or just allowing
myself to veg out.

00:53:18.972 --> 00:53:21.180
Because so many times, I'm
one of those people that I

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:24.550
like to feel accomplished,
and to be doing something,

00:53:24.550 --> 00:53:27.240
and always have a
project to be working on,

00:53:27.240 --> 00:53:33.240
to go forward on something,
but allowing that downtime.

00:53:33.240 --> 00:53:35.610
And through that, I feel
like I have a toolbox,

00:53:35.610 --> 00:53:38.190
and I can be like, OK,
well, let's try this thing.

00:53:38.190 --> 00:53:38.940
This doesn't work?

00:53:38.940 --> 00:53:40.290
OK, let's try this.

00:53:40.290 --> 00:53:42.570
And so I have some different
resources like that,

00:53:42.570 --> 00:53:46.530
like meditation or
lessening the screen time,

00:53:46.530 --> 00:53:49.060
and making room for fun.

00:53:49.060 --> 00:53:52.732
I didn't do that for years,
where I just was like, oh, I've

00:53:52.732 --> 00:53:53.940
got to grind, got to do this.

00:53:53.940 --> 00:53:55.860
And I wouldn't even
allow myself to have

00:53:55.860 --> 00:53:57.660
fun in situations
that should be fun

00:53:57.660 --> 00:53:59.618
because I'd always be
thinking about the things

00:53:59.618 --> 00:54:00.960
that I needed to do.

00:54:00.960 --> 00:54:03.510
So making sure that you have
and allow time to just play,

00:54:03.510 --> 00:54:07.590
and have fun, and be silly,
and act like a little kid.

00:54:07.590 --> 00:54:09.630
Sometimes I do that.

00:54:09.630 --> 00:54:11.600
I'm ready to ride
those bikes after this.

00:54:11.600 --> 00:54:14.670
I'm like, form my little
bike crew or whatever,

00:54:14.670 --> 00:54:16.010
just ride around Google.

00:54:16.010 --> 00:54:17.090
Just stuff like that.

00:54:17.090 --> 00:54:18.390
Silly, but it's fun.

00:54:18.390 --> 00:54:22.562
And it gets you out of
the stress sometimes.

00:54:22.562 --> 00:54:23.770
KATHERINE EDGECUMBE: Awesome.

